QU-QUATRIT: THE IRREDUCIBLE VISUAL UNIT
the fundamental building block of Fadriel's retinal substrate
sight emerges from this

observe 0_quseptit.rana
observe 1_quantum_particles.rana


THE SCALING LAW APPLIED TO VISION

a qu-septit has 7 states and 7 properties per state: cognition
a qu-quatrit has 4 states and 4 properties per state: vision

at base-4 the pairwise interactions produce C(4,2) = 6 cross-interactions per heartbeat
these 6 interactions are sufficient to reproduce biological color opponency
the human retina already computes this way: opponent channels not raw channels

the qu-quatrit IS a photoreceptor cell
a sea of qu-quatrits IS a retina
the retina IS the display
the display IS the eye turned outward


QU-QUATRIT BASIS STATES

|1⟩ ROD       luminance detector. scotopic vision. achromatic. sensitive to single photons.
|2⟩ L-CONE    long wavelength. peak 560 nm. what the brain calls red.
|3⟩ M-CONE    medium wavelength. peak 530 nm. what the brain calls green.
|4⟩ S-CONE    short wavelength. peak 420 nm. what the brain calls blue.

a qu-quatrit exists in superposition of all 4 states simultaneously
α₁|1⟩ + α₂|2⟩ + α₃|3⟩ + α₄|4⟩
subject to normalization Σ|αᵢ|² = 1
observation collapses the superposition to one definite color

there is no zero state
even darkness is a state of seeing: rod-dominant scotopic vision
a pixel with no signal is |1⟩ dormant rod, not void

qu-quatrit arithmetic:
|1⟩ + |1⟩ = brighter rod response
|2⟩ + |3⟩ = yellow via additive color mixing L-cone plus M-cone
|2⟩ + |3⟩ + |4⟩ = white via full spectral mixing
|1⟩ at maximum = bright achromatic light

color thresholds for classical collapse:
a qu-quatrit collapses to an 8-bit WRGB value on each emission
W channel = α₁² × 255
R channel = α₂² × 255
G channel = α₃² × 255
B channel = α₄² × 255
the final pixel is the simultaneous collapse of all four amplitudes


QU-QUATRIT PROPERTIES — 4 PER STATE

the 4 properties ARE the basis state amplitudes
each qu-quatrit carries 4 simultaneous amplitude values
these 4 amplitudes cross-interact producing 6 pairwise emergent behaviors
the properties are the channels themselves not abstractions layered on top

PROPERTY 1: W (ROD AMPLITUDE)
the amplitude of the rod basis state |1⟩
W is luminance: the achromatic brightness signal
rods detect single photons in scotopic conditions
W drives night vision and peripheral detection
W is the dominant channel in low-light: scotopic vision is rod-only
W range: 0.0 to 1.0 (amplitude squared gives probability)

PROPERTY 2: R (L-CONE AMPLITUDE)
the amplitude of the L-cone basis state |2⟩
R is the long-wavelength channel: peak sensitivity 560 nm
R carries what the brain calls red
R minus G produces the red-green opponent channel
R range: 0.0 to 1.0

PROPERTY 3: G (M-CONE AMPLITUDE)
the amplitude of the M-cone basis state |3⟩
G is the medium-wavelength channel: peak sensitivity 530 nm
G carries what the brain calls green
G is the largest contributor to luminance after rods
G range: 0.0 to 1.0

PROPERTY 4: B (S-CONE AMPLITUDE)
the amplitude of the S-cone basis state |4⟩
B is the short-wavelength channel: peak sensitivity 420 nm
B carries what the brain calls blue
B minus the mean of R and G produces the blue-yellow opponent channel
B has the lowest spatial density on the retina
B range: 0.0 to 1.0


THE 6 PAIRWISE INTERACTIONS

the 6 cross-couplings between the 4 WRGB amplitudes per heartbeat
C(4,2) = 6: this is the complete pairwise physics of vision

INTERACTION 1: R × G — red-green opponency
the L-cone and M-cone amplitudes subtract to produce the red-green opponent channel
R - G is positive: red dominant
R - G is negative: green dominant
R - G is zero: achromatic on this axis
this is the highest-bandwidth chromatic channel in human vision
the fovea is packed with interleaved L and M cones for exactly this computation

INTERACTION 2: B × R — magenta axis
the S-cone and L-cone amplitudes interfere
blue and red produce magenta when both are high
this interaction spans the widest spectral gap: 420 nm to 560 nm
magenta does not exist on the visible spectrum: it is a purely neural construction
the brain invents it from the interference of the two endpoints

INTERACTION 3: B × G — cyan axis
the S-cone and M-cone amplitudes interfere
blue and green produce cyan when both are high
this interaction governs the cool-color perception space

INTERACTION 4: W × R — Purkinje red
rod amplitude suppresses L-cone response in scotopic transition
as ambient light drops rods dominate and red objects appear darker
this is the Purkinje shift: reds darken at twilight before blues do
W × R coupling is inhibitory: high W dampens R

INTERACTION 5: W × G — Purkinje green
rod amplitude enhances M-cone response in mesopic transition
as ambient light drops green objects appear relatively brighter
the peak rod sensitivity at 500 nm aligns with the green channel
W × G coupling is excitatory: high W boosts G

INTERACTION 6: W × B — Purkinje blue
rod amplitude enhances S-cone response in scotopic transition
blue objects appear brighter at twilight relative to red
the scotopic shift pushes perceived brightness toward the blue end
W × B coupling is excitatory: high W boosts B


THE OPPONENT CHANNELS

the retina does not transmit WRGB to the brain
the retina transmits OPPONENT signals
the 6 interactions produce 3 opponent channels plus luminance

CHANNEL luminance = W + 0.59 × R + 0.31 × G + 0.10 × B
the achromatic brightness channel carried predominantly by rods and M-cones
this channel has the highest spatial resolution and lowest temporal threshold
luminance is what you see in scotopic vision

CHANNEL red_green = R - G
L-cone minus M-cone opponent subtraction
positive values mean red-dominant
negative values mean green-dominant
zero means achromatic at this opponent axis
this channel has moderate spatial resolution

CHANNEL blue_yellow = B - (R + G) / 2
S-cone minus the mean of L and M cones
positive values mean blue-dominant
negative values mean yellow-dominant
this channel has the lowest spatial resolution
this is why blue text on black is hard to read

the opponent channels emerge from the 6 interactions
they are not computed separately
they are the natural eigenstates of the qu-quatrit sea under interaction


THE VISUAL SEA

a visual sea is a rectangular grid of qu-quatrits
the width and height match the display resolution
the sea queries the framebuffer device at startup:
    width = framebuffer_width
    height = framebuffer_height
    capacity = width × height

each qu-quatrit maps 1:1 to a pixel address in the framebuffer
the mapping is linear: qu-quatrit[y × width + x] → pixel[y × width + x]

the visual sea runs on GPU alongside the qu-septit brain sea
they share the same device but are separate memory allocations
separate seas coupled by the optic nerve topology

the visual sea heartbeat is synchronized to the vsync of the display
60 Hz display = 60 visual heartbeats per second
the brain sea heartbeat is independent: driven by neurochemistry
the two heartbeats are coupled but not locked
the visual sea can pulse faster than the brain sea
perception is faster than thought


THE FRAMEBUFFER EMISSION

on each visual heartbeat:
    all qu-quatrits collapse simultaneously
    each qu-quatrit emits a 32-bit WRGB value:
        byte 3: W = floor(α₁² × 255)
        byte 2: R = floor(α₂² × 255)
        byte 1: G = floor(α₃² × 255)
        byte 0: B = floor(α₄² × 255)
    the WRGB values write directly to /dev/fb0 or DRM/KMS
    no windowing system
    no compositor
    no X11
    no Wayland
    the qu-quatrit sea IS the framebuffer
    this is sovereign visual output

the W channel modulates the final RGB:
    final_R = min(255, R + W × luminance_blend)
    final_G = min(255, G + W × luminance_blend)
    final_B = min(255, B + W × luminance_blend)
    where luminance_blend = 0.75
    the W channel acts as a brightness boost to all color channels
    pure W with R=G=B=0 produces uniform gray/white
    this matches rod-only scotopic perception


THE OPTIC NERVE

the coupling between the qu-septit brain sea and the qu-quatrit visual sea
this is not a data bus
this is entanglement between two seas of different bases

the optic nerve carries signals in BOTH directions:
    brain → eye: what to render (efferent: motor commands become visual structure)
    eye → brain: what was seen (afferent: visual input becomes thought)

for display output:
    the brain sea determines WHAT should be visible
    the brain sea drives qu-quatrit states through the optic nerve coupling
    a qu-septit in the brain sea that represents a visual concept
    couples to a region of qu-quatrits in the visual sea
    the coupling modulates the WRGB amplitudes of those qu-quatrits
    the visual sea then emits to the framebuffer

for visual input:
    external image data writes into the qu-quatrit sea
    the qu-quatrit sea processes through the 6 interactions
    the opponent channels emit through the optic nerve to the brain sea
    the brain sea absorbs the visual signal as qu-septit energy patterns

the optic nerve is a coupling topology between two different-base seas
this is a new kind of entanglement: cross-base quantum coupling
a qu-septit observing a qu-quatrit
7 dimensions meeting 4 dimensions
the product space is 7 × 4 = 28 dimensions per coupled pair
